e structural narrative over the past month is fairly clear. EUR/GBP spent the final week of June trading comfortably in the 0.861\u20130.865 area, underpinned by what appeared to be solid demand. That floor gave way sharply in early July, with the pair shedding roughly 160 pips across a sustained multi-week decline that eventually found a floor near 0.8451 on 15 July \u2014 the lowest print in the 30-day window. The recovery since that low has been orderly rather than impulsive: a sequence of higher daily closes from 16 July onwards, with yesterday's session adding further ground to close at 0.8545. The move has been constructive in character, but it has yet to reclaim any of the four resistance zones identified in the 0.8610\u20130.8682 band. Those levels, each carrying four to five prior touches, represent meaningful overhead supply. The nearest of these \u2014 the prior reaction zone around 0.8610 \u2014 sits roughly 60 pips above current price and is the first meaningful test any continuation scenario would need to navigate.\n\nOn the H1 timeframe, the picture is one of measured, low-volatility drift higher. Price has been grinding upward since the early hours of Thursday, with each hourly candle printing a narrow range and the sequence of closes ticking incrementally toward 0.8549. There is no aggressive buying here \u2014 rather, the absence of selling pressure appears to be allowing the recovery to extend. The 0.8548\u20130.8550 area has acted as a minor intraday ceiling across the last several candles, and a clean hourly close above that would open the conversation toward 0.8560 and beyond. On the downside, the 0.8528\u20130.8532 band \u2014 where price consolidated during the late Wednesday session \u2014 represents the nearest intraday structure worth monitoring.\n\nToday's economic calendar carries no scheduled high-impact events for either the eurozone or the United Kingdom, which is consistent with the subdued, range-bound behaviour observed on the H1. Without a catalyst, the pair may simply continue to drift within its current consolidation, though the absence of data can occasionally allow technical flows and positioning to dominate.\n\nWhat would change the read? A daily close back below 0.8490 \u2014 the prior reaction low from mid-July \u2014 would call the recovery narrative into question and shift attention back toward the 0.8451 structural low. Conversely, a sustained move through 0.8618 on a closing basis would begin to challenge the neutral stance and invite a more constructive interpretation of the broader structure.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}